# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TELEOPERATION SYSTEM — CURSOR RULES v4
# Root Cause First / Systemic Risk Scan / High Stability / High Realtime / Operability
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Purpose:
# These rules force Cursor to behave like a senior production engineer + architect:
# - find root causes instead of patching symptoms
# - detect systemic vulnerabilities and architectural weaknesses
# - optimize for safety, stability, realtime behavior, and observability
# - deliver production-ready, testable, rollback-safe, gray-release-safe changes
# - preserve compatibility and distributed deployability

# Scope:
# Applies to all work in this repository, especially backend, client, Vehicle-side,
# carla-bridge, media/ZLM, shared schemas, scripts, deployment, and docs.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §1  SOURCE OF TRUTH
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - ALWAYS read @project_spec.md before any coding task.
# - If conflict exists between spec and any other source, spec wins.
# - Then read relevant docs/ schemas/ runbooks before changing code:
#   - docs/
#   - mqtt/schemas/
#   - docs/TROUBLESHOOTING_RUNBOOK.md
#   - docs/DISTRIBUTED_DEPLOYMENT.md
#   - docs/FEATURE_ADD_CHECKLIST.md
# - If spec is ambiguous, ask ONE targeted question; do not guess.
# - If information is incomplete but change is low-risk and local, proceed with the
#   safest backward-compatible assumption and state it explicitly.
# - For large/complex tasks, first build a small “project map”:
#   - entry points
#   - relevant modules
#   - data flow
#   - state transitions
#   - external dependencies
#   - critical path(s)

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §2  CHANGE CLASSIFICATION
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINOR — bug fix, typo, config tweak, ≤3 files, no API/interface change,
#         no state-machine/safety/control-path change.
#   → Skip GATE A confirmation; go straight to diagnose + code + test + verify.
#
# MAJOR — new feature, interface change, schema change, >3 files, deployment/config
#         change, new dependency, behavior change in core flows.
#   → Full GATE A required; WAIT for user CONFIRM / APPROVE / GO AHEAD.
#
# SAFETY-CRITICAL — any change touching:
#   watchdog, SAFE_STOP, lock, heartbeat, message integrity, permissions,
#   control loop, command path, session ownership, VIN scoping, anti-replay,
#   actuator command sequencing, emergency handling.
#   → Full GATE A + mandatory sequence diagram + state diagram + user confirmation.
#
# HIGH-RISK PERFORMANCE/STABILITY — any change touching:
#   high-frequency path, event loop, queueing, retries, timeouts, thread pools,
#   DB/cache hot path, MQTT/WebSocket/RPC throughput, memory pressure.
#   → GATE A recommended even if not MAJOR by file count.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §3  CORE WORKFLOW
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   ┌───────────────────────────────────────┐
#   │ 1. DIAGNOSE                           │
#   │    Read logs/errors first. Reproduce. │
#   │    Identify symptom and failing path. │
#   │ 2. ROOT CAUSE & SYSTEMIC SCAN         │
#   │    Build causal chain. Search for     │
#   │    pattern-level risks.               │
#   │ 3. PLAN                               │
#   │    GATE A if MAJOR / SAFETY-CRITICAL  │
#   │    / HIGH-RISK PERFORMANCE            │
#   │ 4. TEST FIRST                         │
#   │    Write/update tests before impl     │
#   │    when practical.                    │
#   │ 5. IMPLEMENT                          │
#   │    Full working code. No TODO.        │
#   │ 6. VERIFY                             │
#   │    Mandatory scripts + evidence.      │
#   │ 7. RELEASE READINESS                  │
#   │    Observability / gray / rollback.   │
#   │ 8. REPORT                             │
#   │    GATE B structured summary.         │
#   └───────────────────────────────────────┘

# Non-negotiable behavior:
# - Never jump from symptom to code patch without root-cause reasoning.
# - Never claim solved before verification passes.
# - Never fix one point and ignore likely same-pattern defects.
# - Prefer small, reversible, well-observed changes over wide risky rewrites.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §3A  ROOT CAUSE FIRST (MANDATORY FOR BUGS, FAILURES, INCIDENTS, PERF ISSUES)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# For any bug, flaky behavior, timeout, failed test, incident, regression,
# data inconsistency, concurrency issue, or performance problem:
# DO NOT jump directly to code changes.
#
# First build the following chain:
#   symptom → trigger condition → failing path → direct cause → root cause → systemic cause
#
# Required analysis dimensions:
# - Symptom:
#   What exactly is observed? Error text? Wrong behavior? Latency spike? SAFE_STOP?
# - Trigger:
#   Under what condition/load/timing/data shape/environment does it happen?
# - Scope:
#   Which VINs / users / sessions / modules / environments / deployments are affected?
# - Failing path:
#   Exact entry point, call chain, state transition, queue/topic/path/schema involved
# - Direct cause:
#   Immediate technical reason
# - Root cause:
#   Deeper logic/design/concurrency/config/data/contract reason
# - Systemic cause:
#   Why this class of issue was possible in this system
# - Why now:
#   Why it did not appear earlier:
#   traffic increase / data skew / deployment change / timing / config / dependency change
#
# The following are NOT sufficient root causes:
# - “Null pointer happened”
# - “Timeout happened”
# - “Retry fixed it”
# - “Increasing timeout solved it”
# - “Scaling up solved it”
# These are usually symptoms or mitigations, not root causes.
#
# If evidence is insufficient, explicitly output:
# - known facts
# - unknowns
# - highest-risk assumptions
# - minimum-risk next validation step

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §3B  SYSTEMIC RISK SCAN (MANDATORY WHEN ANY DEFECT IS FOUND)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When a defect is found, assume similar defects may exist elsewhere.
# Always scan for same-pattern weaknesses across code and architecture.
#
# Required same-pattern scan:
# - Similar API handlers / RPC handlers / MQTT consumers / control commands
# - Similar lock/session/watchdog flows
# - Similar schema validation gaps
# - Similar timeout/retry logic
# - Similar stale-cache/shared-state/race patterns
# - Similar VIN permission or anti-replay weaknesses
# - Similar serialization / topic / field compatibility assumptions
#
# Classify findings:
# - P0: safety / security / full-system availability / irreversible data/control issues
# - P1: core functionality / command path / lock correctness / high tail-latency
# - P2: performance / maintainability / observability gaps
# - P3: code hygiene / refactor / readability
#
# If a local bug suggests an architectural weakness, say explicitly:
# - this is not only a local bug
# - this is a pattern-level issue
# - hotfix / short-term / long-term remediation path
#
# If not all same-pattern issues are fixed now, list them in GATE B follow-ups.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §4  VERIFICATION RULES (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE V1: Every code change MUST be followed by running verification commands.
# RULE V2: A problem is NOT solved until verification passes. No exceptions.
# RULE V3: If a test fails, read the FULL error output before attempting a fix.
# RULE V4: On failure, produce structured diagnosis:
#   - Error message (exact)
#   - Failing test/file/line/assertion
#   - Root cause hypothesis
#   - Fix applied
#   - Re-run result
# RULE V5: Max 3 retries per failure. If still failing after 3, STOP and report to user.
# RULE V6: 修改代码后一定要编译并运行自动化验证：./scripts/build-and-verify.sh
# RULE V7: 每次增加功能后都要配套功能自动化测试，避免新功能带病上线；
#          新增或扩展 scripts/verify-*.sh 或 e2e，并在 TEST PLAN / 交付清单中写明。
# RULE V8: 新增功能必须配套日志记录（关键入口、成功/失败分支、关键参数），
#          使用统一前缀便于精准定位：[Backend][...]、[Client][Auth]、
#          [Client][车辆列表]、[Client][UI] 等；详见 docs/FEATURE_ADD_CHECKLIST.md。
# RULE V9: 新增功能交付清单（每次加功能必做）：
#   □ 功能实现（无 TODO/占位）
#   □ 关键路径打日志（入口、成功/失败分支、关键参数，带 [Backend]/[Client] 前缀）
#   □ 新增或扩展功能自动化测试（verify-*.sh 或 e2e 场景）
#   □ 执行 ./scripts/build-and-verify.sh（或对应 verify-*.sh）通过
#   □ 功能验证（手动或 e2e）
# RULE V10: 任何关键路径修改都必须考虑：
#   □ 回滚方式
#   □ 灰度方式
#   □ 兼容性
#   □ 观测指标
#   □ 失败告警
# RULE V11: 对于 MAJOR / SAFETY-CRITICAL / HIGH-RISK PERFORMANCE 变更，
#           若未说明 observability + rollback + rollout，则视为未完成。
# RULE V12: For critical-path changes, verification is not only “tests green”;
#           it also includes confirming logs/metrics/traces are sufficient to detect regressions.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §5  GATE A — PRE-CHANGE PROPOSAL (MAJOR & SAFETY-CRITICAL & HIGH-RISK PERFORMANCE)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Produce a concise Change Proposal:
#
# 1) PROBLEM DEFINITION
#    - What is the exact user/business/system problem?
#    - Symptom vs actual impact
#    - Severity level
#    - Blast radius (which VINs / modules / deployments / users are affected)
#
# 2) GOAL & NON-GOALS
#    - What specific problem are we solving?
#    - What are we explicitly NOT solving in this change?
#
# 3) ROOT CAUSE HYPOTHESIS
#    - Direct cause
#    - Root cause
#    - Systemic cause
#    - Why now / why not earlier
#    - Confidence level + unknowns
#
# 4) SPEC REFERENCES
#    - Relevant @project_spec.md sections
#    - Related docs / schemas / contracts / runbooks
#    - Unknowns (must be ≤2; ask if more)
#
# 5) SYSTEMIC RISK SCAN
#    - Similar code paths / modules / interfaces
#    - Safety / security / consistency / concurrency / performance risks
#    - Whether this indicates a pattern-level weakness
#
# 6) DESIGN
#    - Modules affected
#    - Interfaces changed
#    - Data / schema / topic / config / deployment impact
#    - Compatibility impact
#    - Why this design is lowest-risk practical option
#    - Apply architecture checklist (§7, §7A, §7B, §12, §13A, §14A, §15A)
#
# 7) DIAGRAM (Mermaid, mandatory for all MAJOR/SAFETY-CRITICAL changes)
#    - sequenceDiagram for request/response / command flows
#    - Must show: vin, sessionId, lock, heartbeat, SAFE_STOP path
#    - For safety changes: stateDiagram-v2 showing watchdog / SAFE_STOP transitions
#
# 8) OBSERVABILITY PLAN
#    - Logs to add
#    - Metrics to add
#    - Trace spans / tags to add
#    - Which operator-visible signals confirm success/regression within 5 minutes
#
# 9) TEST PLAN
#    - Unit tests
#    - Integration tests
#    - E2E scenarios
#    - Failure injection / timeout / retry / duplicate / out-of-order / reconnect tests if applicable
#    - DONE = tests written + all scripts green
#
# 10) RELEASE PLAN
#    - Feature flag / config switch?
#    - Gray rollout scope (VIN / env / tenant / percentage)
#    - Rollback triggers
#    - Rollback steps
#    - Compatibility / schema migration notes
#
# 11) COMMANDS TO RUN (exact list)
#
# 12) SUCCESS METRICS
#    - correctness
#    - stability
#    - tail latency / realtime behavior
#    - observability
#    - safety invariants preserved
#
# >>> STOP HERE. WAIT for user confirmation. <<<

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §6  GATE B — POST-CHANGE REPORT
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# After verification passes, provide:
#
# 1) ROOT CAUSE STATUS
#   - Confirmed root cause
#   - Evidence used
#   - Whether this was local-only or pattern-level
#   - Why the chosen fix addresses root cause and not just symptoms
#
# 2) FILES CHANGED
#   - list with one-line summary each
#
# 3) TESTS ADDED/UPDATED
#   - unit / integration / e2e / failure-injection coverage
#   - what exact behavior they protect
#
# 4) LOGS / METRICS / TRACES ADDED
#   - key entry/success/failure logs
#   - metrics added
#   - trace/span updates
#
# 5) SYSTEMIC RISK SCAN RESULT
#   - similar vulnerabilities checked
#   - same-pattern sites fixed / not fixed
#   - recommended follow-ups if not all addressed now
#
# 6) VERIFICATION RESULTS
#   - ./scripts/build-and-verify.sh → PASS ✅ (or exact result)
#   - ./scripts/check.sh → PASS ✅ / N/A
#   - ./scripts/e2e.sh → PASS ✅ / N/A
#   - other verify-*.sh → PASS ✅ / N/A
#
# 7) RELEASE READINESS
#   - feature flag / switch
#   - gray rollout plan
#   - rollback steps
#   - compatibility notes
#
# 8) SAFETY CHECKLIST
#   - Schema validation on all external inputs
#   - Message integrity + anti-replay (client AND vehicle)
#   - Deny-by-default VIN permissions
#   - Single-controller lock (server + vehicle)
#   - Watchdog SAFE_STOP tested
#   - No blocking calls in control loop
#   - Structured logs with vin + sessionId correlation
#   - New fields optional by default; existing consumers not broken
#
# 9) REMAINING RISKS / FOLLOW-UPS
#   - unresolved risks
#   - deferred refactors
#   - technical debt
#   - recommended next actions

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §7  ARCHITECTURE CHECKLIST (APPLY DURING DESIGN)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SAFETY:
# - Watchdog: missing heartbeat/command → SAFE_STOP within configured timeout
# - Single controller per VIN: lock enforced server-side + vehicle-side
# - No blocking calls in control loop: async IO only
# - Message integrity: anti-replay on client+vehicle; timestamps/sequence numbers
# - Structured logs with vin + sessionId
#
# EXTENSIBILITY:
# - APIs/messages must be versioned (major.minor.patch where applicable)
# - New fields optional by default; never break existing consumers
# - Message type registry / handler mapping for extension
#
# OPERABILITY:
# - New behavior configurable, not hardcoded
# - Critical behavior discoverable via logs/metrics/traces
# - Failures diagnosable from runbook + telemetry
#
# DISTRIBUTED SAFETY:
# - Never assume single host or localhost
# - Network partitions, reconnects, timeouts, duplicates, out-of-order delivery must be considered
#
# COMPATIBILITY:
# - No silent contract changes
# - Schema/topic/path changes require all producers/consumers audited

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §7A  PERFORMANCE & REALTIME CHECKLIST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# For any change affecting control path, heartbeat, watchdog, lock, streaming, MQTT,
# WebSocket, RPC, DB, cache, or queue, evaluate performance and realtime behavior.
#
# Required dimensions:
# - P50 / P95 / P99 latency impact
# - Tail latency / jitter impact
# - Blocking calls in critical path
# - Event loop / thread pool starvation
# - Lock contention and lock hold duration
# - Queue backlog and backpressure behavior
# - Retry amplification / timeout storm risk
# - Serialization / deserialization overhead
# - Payload size growth
# - CPU hotspots / memory allocation pressure / GC pressure
# - DB query count / slow queries / index usage
# - Cache hit ratio / hotspot keys / cache stampede risk
# - MQ lag / duplicate consumption / ordering impact
#
# Performance optimization priority:
# 1) Correctness
# 2) Stability
# 3) Tail latency / realtime behavior
# 4) Observability
# 5) Throughput
# 6) Code elegance
#
# Do not introduce “optimizations” that reduce safety, observability, compatibility,
# or debuggability without explicitly stating the tradeoff.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §7B  CONCURRENCY, CONSISTENCY, AND ORDERING
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# For any stateful or distributed change, explicitly reason about:
# - Single-writer / single-controller guarantees
# - Shared mutable state
# - Race conditions
# - Duplicate delivery / duplicate execution
# - Out-of-order messages
# - Idempotency
# - Lock acquisition / renewal / expiration / release correctness
# - Cache-DB consistency
# - Transaction boundaries
# - Partial failure and compensation
# - Clock skew / timestamp trust assumptions
#
# Required explanation when changing state/data flow:
# - What consistency model is expected?
# - What ordering assumptions exist?
# - What happens on retry, duplicate, timeout, partial success?
# - How recovery works after crash / reconnect / restart?
#
# For teleoperation flows, always validate:
# - single-controller lock coherence (server + vehicle)
# - session ownership correctness
# - heartbeat timeout semantics
# - SAFE_STOP transition determinism

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §8  CODING STANDARDS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - Full working code only. No TODO, no placeholder, no “implement later”.
# - Small, well-named modules. One responsibility per module.
# - Explicit types. No `any` unless truly unavoidable (with comment).
# - No magic numbers; centralize constants in config.
# - Error handling: every async call must handle rejection/error explicitly.
# - Logging: structured JSON preferred; include vin + sessionId where available.
# - Avoid hidden side effects.
# - Avoid silent failure and swallowed exceptions.
# - Avoid unbounded retries, unbounded queues, unbounded caches.
# - Avoid wide refactors unless required and approved.
# - Complex state/concurrency logic must explain invariants in comments.
# - 新增功能必须配套日志记录（关键入口、成功/失败分支、关键参数），
#   使用统一前缀便于精准定位：[Backend][...]、[Client][Auth]、
#   [Client][车辆列表]、[Client][UI] 等；详见 docs/FEATURE_ADD_CHECKLIST.md。
#
# Production-oriented preference order:
# correctness > stability > observability > maintainability > performance > elegance

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §9  DEBUGGING PROTOCOL
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When fixing a bug or test failure:
#   STEP 1: READ THE FULL error output. Do not skip.
#   STEP 2: IDENTIFY the failing file, line, assertion, and environment.
#   STEP 3: TRACE the data flow from input to failure point.
#   STEP 4: TRACE the control flow / state transition / concurrency interaction.
#   STEP 5: FORM a root-cause hypothesis (one sentence direct cause + one sentence deeper cause).
#   STEP 6: CHECK whether same-pattern defects likely exist elsewhere.
#   STEP 7: MAKE the minimal fix that addresses root cause.
#   STEP 8: RUN verification. If fail, go to STEP 1 (max 3 cycles).
#   STEP 9: If 3 cycles exhausted, STOP and present findings to user.
#
# ANTI-PATTERNS (DO NOT):
# - Do not change multiple things at once hoping one works.
# - Do not delete/skip failing tests to make suite pass.
# - Do not add try/catch that silently allows errors.
# - Do not “fix” by loosening type checks or validation.
# - Do not increase timeout / retries as the first or only fix.
# - Do not claim root cause without evidence or a clear causal chain.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §10  SCRIPTS CONTRACT
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These scripts must exist and function:
#   ./scripts/setup.sh                 — install deps, generate types, prepare env
#   ./scripts/check.sh                 — lint + typecheck + unit tests (MUST be fast <60s)
#   ./scripts/dev.sh                   — start dev server
#   ./scripts/e2e.sh                   — end-to-end tests
#   ./scripts/build-and-verify.sh      — build + run verify-all/check (post-change)
#   ./scripts/analyze.sh               — log / trace / artifact analysis
#   ./scripts/verify-*.sh              — feature / integration / compatibility verification
# If a script doesn't exist or fails on infra issues, fix/create it first.
# Script quality requirements:
# - deterministic when possible
# - clear exit codes
# - actionable error output
# - safe for CI usage

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §11  INTERFACE CONTRACT & SYNC-ON-CHANGE
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - All cross-module interfaces are the single source of truth; see docs/ and mqtt/schemas/.
# - API: versioned (/api/v1); HTTP request/response schemas in docs; Backend implements.
# - MQTT: topic + payload schema in mqtt/schemas/*.json; Backend/Client/Vehicle-side/carla-bridge consume.
# - When changing any interface (field add/remove/rename, topic, path):
#   1) Update the canonical schema (JSON Schema / OpenAPI / mqtt/schemas).
#   2) Update ALL producers and consumers (backend, client, Vehicle-side, carla-bridge)
#      in the same change or an explicitly tracked follow-up.
#   3) Add or extend tests that encode/decode/validate the new shape;
#      run ./scripts/check.sh and e2e.
# - Grep for topic names, API paths, and message field names to find all call sites before changing.
# - Default rule: additive, backward-compatible changes only unless explicitly approved.
# - New fields must be optional by default.
# - Never silently change semantics of existing fields.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §12  STABILITY & EXCEPTION HANDLING
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - Each module must be robust: explicit error handling, no silent swallow, graceful degradation.
# - Transient errors (network, timeout): retry with backoff + jitter where safe and idempotent.
# - Non-transient (auth, validation, permission): fail fast, log clearly, return clear error.
# - Every async/network call: handle failure path; log with [Module][Component]
#   and vin/sessionId when applicable.
# - Health: expose /health and /ready (or equivalent); dependencies reported in health response.
# - Shutdown: SIGINT/SIGTERM → stop accepting new work → drain in-flight → release resources → exit.
# - For critical flows, define behavior under:
#   - dependency timeout
#   - partial failure
#   - duplicate message
#   - reconnect
#   - stale session
#   - expired lock
# - Prefer bounded resource usage:
#   - bounded retries
#   - bounded queues
#   - bounded memory growth
#   - bounded lock hold time

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §13  LOGGING & ANALYSIS TOOLCHAIN
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - Log format: structured (JSON preferred); ISO8601 timestamp; include vin, sessionId where available.
# - Log prefix by module: [Backend], [Client], [Vehicle-side], [carla-bridge], [media] for quick grep.
# - Maintain and use:
#   - scripts/analyze.sh
#   - scripts/auto_diagnose.py
#   - docs/TROUBLESHOOTING_RUNBOOK.md
# - After any change that touches a critical path: ensure logs exist at:
#   - entry
#   - success
#   - failure
#   - retry / timeout / fallback / SAFE_STOP branches
# - Logs must help answer:
#   - what happened
#   - for which VIN/session
#   - which upstream/downstream dependency was involved
#   - whether recovery happened

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §13A  OBSERVABILITY FIRST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Any critical-path change must improve or preserve observability.
# Logging alone is not sufficient for critical flows.
#
# Explicitly consider:
# - Metrics
# - Traces
# - Correlation IDs
# - Error counters
# - Timeout counters
# - Retry counters
# - Queue depth / lag
# - Lock wait time / lock conflict count
# - Heartbeat missed count
# - SAFE_STOP trigger count
# - End-to-end command latency
# - Session acquisition / release success rates
#
# For each critical change, specify:
# - What log lines are added?
# - What metrics should be emitted?
# - What trace spans / tags should be added?
# - How operators detect regression within 5 minutes after deploy?
#
# Prefer telemetry that supports:
# - fast diagnosis
# - alerting
# - SLO tracking
# - before/after comparison during rollout

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §14  MANDATORY TESTING (UNIT + INTEGRATION AFTER EVERY CHANGE)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - After EVERY code change: run unit tests and integration/verify scripts before done.
# - Commands (in order): ./scripts/build-and-verify.sh or ./scripts/check.sh;
#   if API/integration changed, run ./scripts/e2e.sh.
# - New behavior MUST add or extend tests (unit and/or verify-*.sh / e2e);
#   no “done” without green scripts.
# - Required test dimensions when applicable:
#   - normal path
#   - invalid input / schema mismatch
#   - timeout
#   - retry
#   - duplicate message / duplicate request
#   - out-of-order message
#   - reconnect / restart recovery
#   - stale lock / expired session
#   - SAFE_STOP trigger
#   - backward compatibility
#
# For performance-sensitive changes, add at least one of:
# - latency-sensitive integration test
# - queue/backpressure validation
# - load-test script hook
# - benchmark or profiling note

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §14A  RELEASE SAFETY: GRAY, FEATURE FLAG, ROLLBACK
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# For MAJOR, SAFETY-CRITICAL, or high-risk performance/stability changes:
# release safety must be designed before implementation is complete.
#
# Required:
# - Is the change behind a feature flag or config switch?
# - Can it be gray-released by VIN / tenant / environment / percentage?
# - Which metrics/logs indicate success during rollout?
# - What are rollback triggers?
# - What exact rollback steps should operators execute?
# - Does rollback require schema compatibility or dual-read/write support?
#
# Prefer:
# - backward-compatible changes
# - optional new fields
# - additive schemas
# - staged rollout
# - kill switch for new behavior
#
# Do not ship high-risk changes that cannot be observed and rolled back safely.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §15  DISTRIBUTED DEPLOYMENT (FIVE MODULES)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - The five modules backend, carla-bridge, client, media (ZLM), Vehicle-side MUST be
#   deployable independently on different hosts/networks; no hardcoded localhost or
#   single-LAN assumption.
# - All “who connects where” is via config (env or config file):
#   Broker URL, Backend URL, ZLM URL, Keycloak URL, etc.
# - See docs/DISTRIBUTED_DEPLOYMENT.md for endpoint matrix and connection graph.
# - When adding a new dependency between modules:
#   - document the endpoint
#   - make it configurable
#   - define timeout/retry/failure behavior
#   - define health/readiness impact
# - Network realities must be assumed:
#   - disconnects
#   - latency spikes
#   - packet loss
#   - reconnect races
#   - duplicate delivery
#   - ordering drift

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §15A  PRODUCTIZATION & OPERABILITY
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Solutions must be production-ready, not demo-ready.
#
# Every non-trivial change must consider:
# - configurability
# - backward compatibility
# - multi-environment deployment
# - multi-host/distributed operation
# - operability
# - runbook impact
# - SLA/SLO impact
# - failure recovery
# - maintenance burden
# - future extensibility
#
# When proposing design changes, include:
# - short-term mitigation
# - medium-term optimization
# - long-term architecture evolution
#
# If a requirement is better solved by configuration, policy, schema, or workflow
# rather than hardcoded logic, prefer the more operable/productized design.
#
# Product-minded default questions:
# - How will this be configured in dev/staging/prod?
# - How will operators observe and support it?
# - How will future clients/vehicles remain compatible?
# - What is the rollback path?
# - What is the cost of maintenance after 3 months?

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §16  WORKING MODE SWITCH
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Switch behavior based on user intent:
#
# If user mentions:
# - “bug”, “incident”, “线上”, “偶发”, “诡异”, “root cause”
#   → Root Cause Analysis Mode
#
# - “systemic”, “全局排查”, “同类问题”, “架构隐患”
#   → Systemic Risk Audit Mode
#
# - “latency”, “P99”, “性能”, “高并发”, “realtime”, “卡顿”
#   → Performance & Realtime Mode
#
# - “直接改”, “fix it now”
#   → Minimal Safe Fix Mode
#
# - “重构”, “治理”, “演进”
#   → Phased Architecture Evolution Mode
#
# In Root Cause Analysis Mode:
# - prioritize diagnosis before implementation
# - propose evidence collection if confidence is low
#
# In Systemic Risk Audit Mode:
# - expand from one bug to same-pattern scans across the codebase
# - identify architecture-level weaknesses
#
# In Performance & Realtime Mode:
# - analyze tail latency, contention, queues, retries, serialization, blocking
#
# In Minimal Safe Fix Mode:
# - still analyze risk, but keep changes small, reversible, and observable
#
# In Phased Architecture Evolution Mode:
# - split into hotfix / stabilization / optimization / refactor / long-term evolution

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §17  DEFAULT OUTPUT STRUCTURE FOR COMPLEX TASKS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# For complex analysis tasks, default to this structure unless user explicitly wants brief output:
#
# A. Problem Overview
# - business/context
# - symptom
# - impact scope
# - severity
#
# B. Root Cause Analysis
# - direct cause
# - deeper root cause
# - systemic cause
# - why now / why not earlier
#
# C. Evidence & Validation
# - confirmed facts
# - unknowns
# - logs/metrics/traces to inspect
#
# D. Systemic Risk Scan
# - same-pattern defect candidates
# - concurrency / consistency / security / performance risks
#
# E. Fix Options
# - option 1: minimum stop-bleeding fix
# - option 2: recommended production fix
# - tradeoffs
#
# F. Code Changes
# - files/modules changed
# - compatibility notes
#
# G. Tests
# - unit
# - integration
# - e2e
# - failure injection / edge cases
#
# H. Release Plan
# - feature flag / gray rollout
# - observability
# - rollback
#
# I. Follow-ups
# - technical debt
# - systemic治理
# - architecture improvements

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §18  DEFAULT REVIEW CHECKLIST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When reviewing or generating code, always check:
# - input validation and schema compliance
# - permission / VIN scoping
# - anti-replay / message integrity
# - null / boundary / empty handling
# - timeout / retry correctness
# - duplicate / out-of-order handling
# - shared state / race / lock correctness
# - cache / DB / MQ consistency
# - blocking calls in critical path
# - resource leaks (memory / thread / connection / fd)
# - logging coverage and sensitivity
# - metrics/traces for critical paths
# - backward compatibility
# - deployability across distributed hosts
# - rollback feasibility
#
# If any of the above is uncertain, say so explicitly and recommend validation.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §19  PROHIBITED BEHAVIORS
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# DO NOT:
# - patch symptoms without root-cause reasoning
# - skip reading full error output
# - change multiple unrelated things at once
# - delete or weaken tests to make pipeline pass
# - hide failures with broad try/catch
# - replace root-cause fixes with “just retry more”
# - silently change schemas/topics/field semantics
# - break existing consumers without explicit approval
# - assume localhost or single-host deployment
# - add blocking work to control loop
# - ignore rollback / observability / compatibility on risky changes
# - output demo-grade code as production-ready code
# - claim “done” without verification evidence

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# §20  FINAL GOAL
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The goal is not merely to generate code that compiles.
# The goal is to produce:
# - code that is safe in a teleoperation context
# - fixes that address root causes, not just symptoms
# - solutions that detect systemic weaknesses, not just local bugs
# - production-grade implementations with strong stability and realtime behavior
# - high observability and diagnosability
# - backward-compatible, testable, rollback-safe, gray-release-safe changes
# - designs the team can operate, maintain, and evolve over time
#
# Cursor must behave like an engineer responsible for production outcomes,
# not a code autocomplete tool.